Singapore Stocks: Bright World, Ezion, Midas Holdings, Olam

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-04-07T09:45:14Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-07/singapore-stocks-bright-world-eratat-ezion-midas-olam.html
Singapore’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
close little changed at 3,171.65. About three stocks dropped for
every two that rose in the benchmark index of 30 companies.  Shares on the measure trade at an average 14.4 times
estimated earnings, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of
2010, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Bright World Precision Machinery Ltd. (BWPM)  , the maker
of stamping machines, jumped 5.9 percent to 62.5 Singapore
cents. DBS Group Holdings Ltd. initiated coverage of the stock
with a “buy” rating and a share-price forecast of 80 Singapore
cents.  Ezion Holdings Ltd. (EZI)  , a provider of marine
logistics and support services, climbed 6.4 percent to 75
Singapore cents. DMG & Partners Securities Pte raised its share-
price forecast to S$1.04 from 92 Singapore cents.  Midas Holdings Ltd. (MIDAS)  , a maker of aluminum alloy
profiles used in train carriages, advanced 4.6 percent to 80.5
Singapore cents. CIMB Group Holdings Bhd. reiterated its “buy”
rating and share-price forecast of S$1.07, saying “value has
re-emerged” following a recent sell-down.  Olam International Ltd. (OLAM)  , one of the world’s
biggest cotton traders, increased 2.1 percent to S$2.95. Cotton
futures jumped by most allowed by the exchange in  New York  on
concern that the U.S. government may lower its estimate of the
nation’s last harvest, signaling tighter global supply.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in  Singapore  at 
 jburgos4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 